How about something like

    node* ptr = list.head;
    while ((ptr = list.RightPointer(ptr)) != nullptr)
    {
        // Do something with the pointer
    }

We start by calling `RightPointer` with `list.head` (because of the initialization of `ptr`). Each call to `RightPointer` will either return the same node (if nothing happened) or the `next` pointer (if something happened).

When you reach the list end the function will return a null pointer which makes the loop condition false and stops the iteration.

---

To make the code possibly easier to read for a beginner, the above loop is equivalent to this:

    // Get the first node back from RightPointer
    node* ptr = list.RightPointer(list.head);

    // Loop while the pointer returned by RightPointer isn&#39;t a null pointer
    while (ptr != nullptr)
    {
        // Do something with the pointer...
        // ...
        // ...
        // ...

        // Get the (possibly) next pointer from RightPointer
        ptr = list.RightPointer(ptr);

        // Note that the above call could return the same node that was passed to it
        // Or it might return ptr-&gt;next
        // This means the above assignment could either be equivalent to
        //     ptr = ptr;
        // or
        //     ptr = ptr-&gt;next;
    }

